net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component

Class Container

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component.ComponentImpl
      • net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.component.Container
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    PropertyChangeListener, Iterable<Component>, EventListener, LocaleContextSource, Component, ListCellRenderer, ParentComponent, TableCellRenderer, TreeCellRenderer
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractLazyInit, AbstractSimpleValueEditor, CalendarDateRange, CardContainer, ClickToEditComponent, ClickToEditForm, CollapsibleContainer, DateComponent, DateRangeConstraint.DateRangeComponent, HistoryContainer, ListTaskManager.TaskListContainer, LocaleSelector, MessageContainer, NumberRangeConstraint.NumberRangeComponent, PopupMenu, TabbedContainerImpl, Window, WindowContainer

    public class Container
extends ComponentImpl
implements ParentComponent, TableCellRenderer, TreeCellRenderer, ListCellRenderer, PropertyChangeListener

    The Container object is a component that contains other Components.

    Child components can be placed using a grid. See the layout objects in com.i2rd.java.miwt.layout. In modern UIs, containers are not typically created with a layout. Instead of(Component...) or add(Component) is used. The layout is then left up to a web designer using CSS.

    The Container implements the list, table and tree cell renderer interfaces. When the container is called to get the component for cell rendering, each child component that also implements the cell renderer interface will get called. It is important to add the child components BEFORE the cell renderer method is called. If extending Container, add children in the constructor, otherwise add after constructing the new object. If you override the cell renderer method in a Container subclass, be sure to call the super class method after adding any child components. You must check the documentation for the behavior of the child components that implement cell renderers/editors. Some settings, such as labels, are changed according to the cell renderer values. In this case if you want to set these properties you must do so after the call to the superclass cell renderer method or your changes will be replaced in favor of the component's cell renderer behavior. Also be aware that init() will not be called until after the getTableCellRenderer() or getTreeCellRenderer() method. This is required because the library does not yet have the component until these methods return it. For one thing this means you can't add component in init() and expect them to take on the values from the cell renderer method.

    Author:
    Pat B. Double (double@i2rd.com)

        public Element getHTMLElement()
        Description copied from interface: Component
        Get the top level elements this component will output in its current state. This should not included the entire content model.

        For example, if your code outputs the following, <p><span><b></b></span></p>, then you should only return one element that is a "p"; NOT "p, span, b".

        All configuration elements should be nested within this top element, or other arrangements should be made with the inner keeper.
